1 S50-230. House amendments to Senate legislation. (1) When the House has properly returned
2 Senate legislation with House amendments, the Senate shall announce the amendments on Order of Business
3 No. 5 and the President shall place them on second reading for debate. The President may rerefer Senate
4 legislation with House amendments to a committee for a hearing if the House amendments constitute a
5 significant change in the Senate legislation. The second reading vote is limited to consideration of the House
6 amendments.
7 (2) If the Senate accepts House amendments, the Senate shall place the final form of the legislation on
8 third reading to determine if the legislation, as amended, is passed or if the required vote is obtained.
9 (3) If the Senate rejects the House amendments, the Senate may request the House to recede from its
10 amendments or may direct appointment of a conference committee and request the House to appoint a like
11 committee.
12 S50-240. Governor's amendments. (1) When the Governor returns a bill with recommended
13 amendments, the Senate shall announce the amendments under Order of Business No. 4.
14 (2) The Senate may debate and adopt or reject the Governor's recommended amendments on second
15 reading on any legislative day.
16 (3) If both the Senate and the House of Representatives accept the Governor's recommended
17 amendments on a bill that requires more than a majority vote for final passage, the Senate shall place the final
18 form of the legislation on third reading to determine if the required vote is obtained.
19 S50-250. Governor's veto. (1) When the Governor returns a bill with a veto, the Senate shall
20 announce the veto under Order of Business No. 4.
21 (2) On any legislative day, a Senator may move to override the Governor's veto by a two-thirds vote
22 under Order of Business No. 9.
